wn-Saracino paints a colorful portrait of how residents new and old, from wealthy gay homeowners to Portuguese fishermen, think about gentrification. The new breed of gentrifiers, Brown-Saracino finds, exhibits an acute self-consciousness about their role in the process and works to minimize gentrification’s risks for certain longtime residents. In an era of rapid change, they cherish the unique and fragile, whether a dilapidated house, a two-hundred-year-old landscape, or the presence of people deeply rooted in the place they live. Contesting many long-standing assumptions about gentrification, Brown-Saracino’s absorbing study reveals the unexpected ways beliefs about authenticity, place, and change play out in the social, political, and economic lives of very different neighborhoods.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aGentrificationzUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aUrban renewalzUnited StatesvCase studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  agentrification, social preservation, authenticity, sociology, urban research, local flavor, old neighborhoods, city changes, ethnography, chicago, andersonville, argyle, new england, united states of america, provincetown, dresden, residents, self consciousness, case studies, homesteaders, representation, preserving the past.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311063872108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022607662140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226076645423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226076645/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-063872-1  DG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  a